../../../../missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/HISTORY-OF-REPORT-SUMMARIES.md:3:## Exploration 001: CKN (1982) Proof Architecture
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/HISTORY-OF-REPORT-SUMMARIES.md:6:All 5 structural features extracted. CKN's ε-regularity uses A(r)+E(r)+C(r)+D(r) < ε₀ with all four scale-invariant. Localization via explicit cutoff functions φ with |∇φ|~1/r. Four Young/absorption steps identified (Y1-Y4), with Y2 (Ladyzhenskaya absorption) being the dominant lossy step. The dimension-1 bound is forced by E(r) = (1/r)∫∫|∇u|² being scale-invariant: singular points require ∫∫|∇u|² ≥ ε₀·r, so Vitali covering gives Σ rᵢ ≤ (1/ε₀)∫∫|∇u|² < ∞ → P¹(Σ)=0. Parabolic Sobolev exponent 10/3 = 2·5/(5-2). The bottleneck is scale-invariance + global energy bound, not proof technique.
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/HISTORY-OF-REPORT-SUMMARIES.md:16:All 5 features extracted. Vasseur uses De Giorgi iteration for localization — level sets of |u| on shrinking cylinders with master inequality U_k ≤ C^k · U_{k-1}^{β_p}. Same covering argument and ε-regularity → P¹(Σ)=0 route as CKN. De Giorgi gives better velocity exponent (5/3 vs CKN's 3/2) but worse pressure exponent (4/3). Vasseur identifies β = 3/2 as the precise threshold for full regularity — local pressure term at 4/3 < 3/2 is the structural obstruction. Weaker pressure assumption (L^p(L¹) vs L^{3/2}) at cost of harder internal obstruction. Parabolic Sobolev 10/3 universal.
../../../../library/meta/obstruction-screening/scale-invariant-appearance-inside-lei-does-not-by-itself-clear-a-host-space-audit.md:1:# Scale-Invariant Appearance Inside LEI Does Not By Itself Clear A Host-Space Audit
../../../../library/meta/obstruction-screening/scale-invariant-appearance-inside-lei-does-not-by-itself-clear-a-host-space-audit.md:4:the inherited suitable-weak / LEI architecture.
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/RESULTS.md:5:All three independent proof strategies (CKN 1982, Lin 1998, Vasseur 2007) reduce to the **same covering argument with the same scaling exponents**. The dimension ≤ 1 bound on the singular set is fundamental to epsilon-regularity approaches, not a proof-specific artifact. Improvement requires a genuinely different proof architecture.
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/RESULTS.md:11:| Feature | CKN (1982) | Lin (1998) | Vasseur (2007) |
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/RESULTS.md:14:| **Pressure requirement** | p in L^{3/2}(Q_r) at every scale | p in L^{3/2}(Q_r) (same as CKN) | P in L^p(L^1), any p > 1 (weaker) |
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/RESULTS.md:16:| **Covering argument** | Vitali in parabolic metric, Sum r_i <= (1/eps)int|nabla u|^2 | **Identical to CKN** | **Identical to CKN** |
