../../../../missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-002/REPORT.md:229:| Y1 (pressure-velocity Hölder in LEI) | Hidden in "suitable weak solution" definition | No |
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-002/REPORT.md:238:## Comparison with CKN (1982)
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-002/REPORT.md:240:| Feature | CKN (1982) | Lin (1998) |
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-002/REPORT.md:246:| **Covering argument** | Vitali for parabolic cylinders, Σ_i r_i ≤ (1/ε₀)∫|∇u|² | Identical to CKN |
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-002/REPORT.md:247:| **Dimension bound mechanism** | E(r) scale-invariant → ∫|∇u|² ~ r → P¹(Σ) = 0 | Same (E(r) re-enters via LEI at covering step) |
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-002/REPORT.md:251:| **Proof length** | ~61 pages (CKN original) | ~17 pages (Lin 1998) |
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-002/REPORT.md:259:Lin's proof reaches P¹(Σ) = 0 through exactly the same structural mechanism as CKN:
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-002/REPORT.md:262:2. C(r) + D(r) ≥ ε₀ on singular set → E(r) ≥ c ε₀ on singular set (via LEI)
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-002/REPORT.md:272:In principle, the compactness approach could detect a sharper dimension bound if the limiting solution ũ after blow-up were known to vanish to a higher order. But Lin's argument only shows ũ ≡ 0 (from C(1;ũ) + D(1;ũ) = 0), not that ũ vanishes "with curvature" or satisfies a stronger condition. The extra structure needed to improve the dimension bound would have to be extracted from the NS equation in the limit — which is the same hard analysis problem that CKN's direct approach also faces.
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-002/REPORT.md:274:**Summary:** Lin's (1998) proof is a streamlining of CKN, not a structural departure. The structural bottleneck — the scale-invariance of E(r) forcing dim(Σ) ≤ 1 — is present and unchanged.
