../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-01.md:13:This step is under-specified in exactly the place where the entire chain gets its objectivity. "Choose one inherited theorem-facing endpoint" is too loose. There are several plausible endpoints on the LEI/CKN floor, and the choice of endpoint already biases which reformulations can look useful. If the endpoint is picked before seeing any candidate behavior, the chain may overconstrain the search. If it is picked after informal exposure to candidates, the chain becomes selection-biased while pretending not to be.
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-01.md:37:Keeping at most one promoted candidate and one backup is also too aggressive for this stage. If the mission is wide-funnel planning, then Step 3 should compare a small handful of candidates against the same burden ledger. Otherwise the chain can confuse "first candidate that cleared a vague threshold" with "best available candidate."
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-01.md:41:### Step 4 - Insert the surviving candidate into the inherited LEI / CKN ledger
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-01.md:43:This is where the chain tries to become honest, and it is also where it is weakest. "Write one explicit localization or contradiction line" understates the complexity of endpoint insertion. LEI/CKN arguments do not usually hinge on a single line; they depend on a tightly coupled stack of local energy, pressure decomposition, scaling, covering, and compactness. A candidate that helps one displayed line can still fail because it wrecks admissibility or cannot be threaded through the rest of the proof skeleton.
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-01.md:81:- Step 3 and Step 4 contain the correct instinct: do not celebrate a reformulation before it survives the same burden ledger that kills older approaches.
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-01.md:86:This is a serious chain, not a toy. Its strongest feature is that it tries to kill fake novelty before the program turns into notation management. Its weakness is that the anti-fake-novelty machinery is still too verbal and too path-dependent. To become reliable, it needs one tighter quantitative burden ledger, one explicit prior-art overlap audit, and less early commitment to a single endpoint and single candidate family. Until then, it is a disciplined heuristic, not yet a robust attack plan.
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-02.md:9:1. definable on the suitable-weak / LEI floor,
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-02.md:20:This is the strongest step in the chain because it demands scope control early. But it hides the hardest issue inside the word "admits." For observables like cumulative positive strain or deformation growth, admissibility is not a light bookkeeping matter. On the suitable weak / LEI floor, there is no honest Lagrangian flow map with the regularity needed to define many deformation-based quantities in the way the rest of the chain seems to want. If the branch already expects this, then Step 1 is mostly a kill switch, not a route-building step.
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-02.md:29:- no compatibility with LEI-level compactness.
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-02.md:47:The term "one named bad term" is too permissive and too vague. A branch can appear to pass this gate by controlling a secondary burden while leaving the dominant obstruction untouched. Without a ranked burden ledger, Step 3 can certify leverage on the wrong target.
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-02.md:55:This is the step where the chain most clearly inherits the ambient program's conclusion pressure. It insists that the gain survive insertion into "one LEI / CKN concentration or stretching line" and that all cutoff, pressure, nonlocality, and temporal-window debt be charged immediately. That sounds rigorous, but it may be rigged against any material observable whose value is inherently semi-global or multi-scale.
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-02.md:95:The route presents itself as transport-first, but its decisive tests are all phrased in terms of insertion into an inherited LEI / CKN-style theorem ledger. That means the chain is not asking "can deterministic material stretching produce a real theorem mechanism?" It is asking "can deterministic material stretching be made to serve our existing proof interface?" Those are different questions. The latter is much narrower and much more likely to fail for structural rather than conceptual reasons.
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-02.md:142:If the goal is to test whether a deterministic material-stretching observable can be plugged into the current LEI / CKN theorem machinery, this chain is useful and probably well-aimed. If the goal is to discover whether deterministic transport structure contains a genuinely different theorem mechanism beyond that inherited machinery, the chain is too narrow, too pre-filtered, and too biased toward confirming failure.
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-03.md:7:The problem is that the chain still overestimates what "exact packet structure" is likely to buy. Exact helical triad bookkeeping is real, but real is not the same as coercive. Waleffe-style interaction geometry, same-helicity suppression, and decimated-sector advantages have been around for a long time. The hard issue is not whether one can write a packet-complete ledger. The hard issue is whether any sign or exclusion effect survives full mixed-helicity completion, shell summation, localization, pressure restoration, and insertion into an LEI/CKN-facing endpoint. That is exactly where these ideas usually die.
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-03.md:17:- The candidate "bad transfer patterns" are not interchangeable. Comparable-scale stretching production, shell-bridging concentration feed, and similar targets sit at different levels of the problem. One might be natural in helical triad language while another is only natural on an LEI/CKN ledger. Letting the route pick whichever is most packet-friendly invites target shopping.
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-03.md:57:- The phrase "map the packet gain back to one physical-space endpoint line on the LEI / CKN ledger" hides a severe mismatch of levels. A packet gain can be exact and still fail to correspond to any sharp improvement on the local continuation bottlenecks that matter for beyond-De Giorgi.
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-03.md:105:The route starts in exact helical packet geometry and tries to finish on an LEI/CKN-style physical-space ledger. That is a major level mismatch. Unless the chain finds an unusually robust invariant that survives this translation, most symbolic gains will be spent before they reach the endpoint.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-run-006-attacker-03.log:285:- Atlas `navier-stokes` (proof architecture comparison: CKN/Lin/Vasseur)
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-run-006-attacker-03.log:1232:- The fixed LEI exact-rewrite audit was also killed. Divergence, Lamb-vector, and vorticity/Biot-Savart rewrites did not produce a Tao-sensitive coefficient gain on the frozen localized flux bundle.
../../../../runtime/results/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-decision-008-step-evaluator.md:10:The new `GOAL.md` keeps the strategizer strictly on Chain Step 2: candidate-by-candidate Tao discrimination for the three frozen rewrites, explicit insertion points in the fixed LEI flux term, and immediate branch invalidation if none survive. Verified the JSON schema and the written files after editing.
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/selector.md:1:# Selector - beyond-de-giorgi / run-009
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/selector.md:5:1. **Chain 01 - SQG-Blueprint Commutator And Scalarization Route With Anti-Conjugation And LEI Endpoint Gate**
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/selector.md:7:   - Strongest guard against fake progress because the anti-conjugation rule forces an estimate-level gain on the inherited LEI / CKN burden.
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/selector.md:10:2. **Chain 03 - Deterministic Material Stretching Route With Viscous-Defect And LEI Admission Gates**
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/selector.md:38:The selected set maximizes meaningful diversity without paying for a weakly differentiated reboot. Chain 01 is the anchor because it attacks the clearest live thesis on the board: whether a genuine Navier-Stokes reformulation can change the mechanism on the inherited LEI / CKN ledger. Chain 03 gives the portfolio a deterministic transport-side branch that remains theorem-floor honest after the stochastic route failed, and its admission and coercivity gates mean that even a negative result produces a precise obstruction. Chain 02 preserves the highest-upside symbolic path, but only in a hardened packet-complete form that can be killed cleanly if mixed-helicity restoration or reconstruction erases the gain.
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/planner.md:1:# Planner Portfolio - beyond-de-giorgi / run-009
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/planner.md:8:- The stochastic backward-flow corridor is blocked on solution-class admission. Step 012 says the branch should stop before exact-identity expansion on the inherited suitable-weak / LEI floor.
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/planner.md:9:- The only locally frozen theorem endpoint on disk remains the suitable-weak / Leray-Hopf plus LEI framework feeding the CKN/Lin epsilon-regularity contradiction package.
