../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-run-009-attacker-01.log:167:diff --git a/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-01.md b/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-01.md
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-run-009-attacker-01.log:171:+++ b/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-01.md
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-run-009-attacker-01.log:185:+This step is under-specified in exactly the place where the entire chain gets its objectivity. "Choose one inherited theorem-facing endpoint" is too loose. There are several plausible endpoints on the LEI/CKN floor, and the choice of endpoint already biases which reformulations can look useful. If the endpoint is picked before seeing any candidate behavior, the chain may overconstrain the search. If it is picked after informal exposure to candidates, the chain becomes selection-biased while pretending not to be.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-run-009-attacker-01.log:209:+Keeping at most one promoted candidate and one backup is also too aggressive for this stage. If the mission is wide-funnel planning, then Step 3 should compare a small handful of candidates against the same burden ledger. Otherwise the chain can confuse "first candidate that cleared a vague threshold" with "best available candidate."
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-run-009-attacker-01.log:213:+### Step 4 - Insert the surviving candidate into the inherited LEI / CKN ledger
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-run-009-attacker-01.log:215:+This is where the chain tries to become honest, and it is also where it is weakest. "Write one explicit localization or contradiction line" understates the complexity of endpoint insertion. LEI/CKN arguments do not usually hinge on a single line; they depend on a tightly coupled stack of local energy, pressure decomposition, scaling, covering, and compactness. A candidate that helps one displayed line can still fail because it wrecks admissibility or cannot be threaded through the rest of the proof skeleton.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-run-009-attacker-01.log:253:+- Step 3 and Step 4 contain the correct instinct: do not celebrate a reformulation before it survives the same burden ledger that kills older approaches.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-run-009-attacker-01.log:258:+This is a serious chain, not a toy. Its strongest feature is that it tries to kill fake novelty before the program turns into notation management. Its weakness is that the anti-fake-novelty machinery is still too verbal and too path-dependent. To become reliable, it needs one tighter quantitative burden ledger, one explicit prior-art overlap audit, and less early commitment to a single endpoint and single candidate family. Until then, it is a disciplined heuristic, not yet a robust attack plan.
