../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-008-explorer-001.log:1785:# CKN (1982) Proof Architecture — Exploration 001
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-008-explorer-001.log:1806:The CKN paper works with the 3D incompressible Navier-Stokes equations on an open set
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-008-explorer-001.log:1819:**Suitable weak solution (CKN Definition 2.2):** A pair (u, p) on Q is a *suitable weak solution* if:
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-008-explorer-001.log:1825:       2 ∫∫_Q |∇u|² φ dx dt ≤ ∫∫_Q [|u|² (∂ₜφ + ∆φ) + (|u|² + 2p) u·∇φ] dx dt   ... (LEI)
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-008-explorer-001.log:1827:This is CKN's Condition (2.1). Point (4) — the local energy inequality — is the key additional condition that separates "suitable" from "mere" weak solutions.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-008-explorer-001.log:1829:**CKN's scale-invariant quantities** (their notation in the paper, §2):
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-008-explorer-001.log:1849:### Precise Statement (CKN 1982, Proposition 2 / Theorem B)
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-008-explorer-001.log:1851:**CKN ε-Regularity Theorem:** There exists an absolute constant ε₀ > 0 (depending only on dimension n = 3, with no other parameters) such that:
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-008-explorer-001.log:1857:**What "regular" means precisely (CKN §2):** z₀ is regular if there exists ρ > 0 such that u ∈ L^∞(Q_ρ(z₀)). Equivalently, u ∈ C^{0,α}(Q_ρ(z₀)) for some α > 0 (CKN prove that L^∞ and Hölder continuity are equivalent at the level of NS — this is the core of their Bootstrap lemma, their Lemma 2.3).
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-008-explorer-001.log:1865:CKN also prove (their Theorem A, Proposition 1) that either of the following alone implies regularity at z₀:
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-008-explorer-001.log:1875:**Condition (III) — Pressure-free version (Lin 1998 simplified this):** CKN show the combined condition A+E+C+D is sufficient; Lin (1998) showed that under mild conditions A(r) ≤ ε₀ alone suffices (his Theorem 1.1).
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-008-explorer-001.log:1882:- **E(r)** — time-integrated H¹ semi-norm; the local dissipation. Appears from the local energy inequality (LEI) directly.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-008-explorer-001.log:1892:### The Vitali Covering Construction (CKN §3)
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-008-explorer-001.log:1894:The covering argument occupies §3 of CKN. The key steps are:
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-008-explorer-001.log:1934:**The dimension in Euclidean terms:** The parabolic 1-dimensional Hausdorff measure P¹ = 0 (which is what CKN prove, i.e., P¹(Σ) = 0, not just finite) corresponds in Euclidean space-time ℝ^{3+1} to Hausdorff dimension ≤ 5/3 ≈ 1.667. The reason: a set of parabolic dimension d has Euclidean space-time dimension d + (d/2)·(1/1) ... actually: if a set S ⊆ ℝ³×ℝ has parabolic Hausdorff dimension d_P, its Euclidean Hausdorff dimension d_E satisfies d_P ≤ d_E × (5/4) in general, with exact conversion depending on geometry. The standard statement is: P¹(Σ) = 0 implies that the 1-dimensional Lebesgue measure of the projection of Σ onto the time axis is zero (this is how Scheffer, 1976, originally stated the result; CKN improve to P¹ = 0 which is stronger).
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-008-explorer-001.log:1936:**CKN's actual statement (Theorem C):** "The singular set Σ has one-dimensional (parabolic) Hausdorff measure zero." Explicitly: P¹(Σ) = 0. This implies in particular that Σ cannot contain any curve (not even a Lipschitz arc) in ℝ⁴.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-008-explorer-001.log:1960:CKN's localization uses smooth cutoff functions in space-time. Let φ = φ(x,t) be a standard cutoff:
