../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:525:missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/HISTORY-OF-REPORT-SUMMARIES.md:16:All 5 features extracted. Vasseur uses De Giorgi iteration for localization — level sets of |u| on shrinking cylinders with master inequality U_k ≤ C^k · U_{k-1}^{β_p}. Same covering argument and ε-regularity → P¹(Σ)=0 route as CKN. De Giorgi gives better velocity exponent (5/3 vs CKN's 3/2) but worse pressure exponent (4/3). Vasseur identifies β = 3/2 as the precise threshold for full regularity — local pressure term at 4/3 < 3/2 is the structural obstruction. Weaker pressure assumption (L^p(L¹) vs L^{3/2}) at cost of harder internal obstruction. Parabolic Sobolev 10/3 universal.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:545:missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/REASONING.md:31:4. Interesting asymmetry in Vasseur: De Giorgi beats CKN on velocity terms (5/3 > 3/2) but introduces a new pressure obstruction (4/3 < 3/2)
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:580:missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/RESULTS.md:66:- De Giorgi iteration achieves **better** velocity exponent: 5/3 > CKN's 3/2
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:584:missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/RESULTS.md:70:- Converts "can we prove full regularity?" into "can we control the local pressure term with exponent > 3/2?" — a sharper formulation than CKN provides
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:587:missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/RESULTS.md:104:- **Unexpected discovery:** Vasseur's framework identifies the **precise obstruction** to full regularity: the local pressure term with De Giorgi exponent 4/3 < 3/2. The threshold beta = 3/2 separates partial from full regularity. This is more informative than CKN's framework, which does not explicitly identify the full-regularity barrier.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:619:missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT-SUMMARY.md:40:Explicit smooth cutoff functions φ supported in Q_r with |∇φ| ~ 1/r, |∆φ| ~ 1/r², |∂_t φ| ~ 1/r². Applied to the local energy inequality (LEI), giving four error terms from the cutoff. Pressure is handled via explicit harmonic decomposition p = p₁ + p₂, where p₁ is controlled by Calderón-Zygmund and p₂ by the harmonic mean-value property. Net localized estimate:
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:675:missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:241:By the CKN pressure decomposition technique (see CKN §3, and Robinson-Rodrigo-Sadowski Ch.13 §13.3), p_2 is controlled by the non-local part of the pressure, which in turn is bounded by global L^{3/2} norms of u far from x₀.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:677:missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:397:**Young Step Y4: The absorption step in the CKN "pressure-regularity" lemma**
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:682:missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:515:**On Ladyzhenskaya-Seregin (1999):** They simplify the pressure decomposition step (avoiding the harmonic splitting p = p₁ + p₂ by working in a different functional framework), but the ε-regularity criterion and covering argument are identical to CKN.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:683:missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:517:**On Robinson-Rodrigo-Sadowski (2016):** Their Chapter 13 presents the CKN proof in full, including the explicit form of the local energy inequality and the parabolic Sobolev embedding. Their §13.3 has the most explicit treatment of the pressure decomposition.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:723:missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:5:Analyze Alexis Vasseur's 2007 proof of partial regularity for Navier-Stokes equations using De Giorgi iteration. Extract five structural features and compare with CKN (1982).
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:724:missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:9:**Sources consulted:** Vasseur 2007 preprint; Vasseur lecture notes (DGPekin.pdf); CKN Seminar Notes Ulm 2019 (Skipper); Seregin-Shilkin survey arXiv:1402.7181; Lee REU paper 2024 (De Giorgi for fluids).
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:725:missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:27:1. **No pressure L^{3/2} norm.** The pressure P enters only via P ∈ L^p_t(L¹_x) for any p > 1. This is weaker than CKN's P ∈ L^{3/2} (in space-time) and weaker than L^p(L^{5/3}) used elsewhere. The L¹ spatial integrability is much weaker — only the time Sobolev regularity (p > 1) is needed.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:726:missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:29:2. **Fixed scale, not shrinking.** The domain [−1,1]×B(1) does not shrink as the proof proceeds. The De Giorgi cylinders Q_k converge to [−1/2,1]×B(1/2) from the outside. This is the fundamental structural departure from CKN, where the epsilon-regularity criterion is stated as a condition at every radius r → 0.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:729:missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:83:The covering argument is entirely at the level of Theorem 2 — the De Giorgi iteration (Theorem 1) is used only to establish Theorem 2, after which the CKN covering machinery runs unchanged.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:737:missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:155:**CKN's pressure difficulty.** In CKN, the pressure P satisfies −ΔP = ∂_i∂_j(u_iu_j) globally. Localizing this to a parabolic cylinder Q_r requires Riesz transform estimates, generating error terms of the form ∫|u|² (on larger balls). This introduces a nonlocal term that is hard to control at each scale and requires P ∈ L^{3/2}(Q_r) explicitly.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:742:missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:170:**Why this works at fixed scale but not at shrinking scale:** The key insight is that ||P||_{L^p(L¹)} is a *single global number* that doesn't scale with k. In CKN, you would need ||P||_{L^{3/2}(Q_{r_k})} at each level r_k → 0, which requires the full pressure integrability. Here, the single global norm suffices because Q_k → Q_∞ ≠ 0.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:755:missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:257:Vasseur's transport terms give **5/3 > 3/2** (better than CKN), but the local pressure term gives **4/3 < 3/2** (worse, in the sense of being farther from full regularity). So:
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:757:missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:259:- **Where De Giorgi hits a new wall:** local pressure (4/3 — a new obstruction not visible in CKN)
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:759:missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:272:**No ε-absorption in the main iteration.** Unlike CKN (which uses Young's inequality with free ε to absorb gradient error terms from cutoffs), Vasseur's De Giorgi iteration uses **no free parameters in the core Proposition 3**. Every estimate is done with fixed universal constants. The only source of lossiness is:
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:768:missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:304:| Pressure local term | 3/2 (L^{3/2} pressure directly) | 4/3 (harmonic/CZ; *looser* than CKN for this term) |
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:771:missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:313:## Synthesis: CKN vs. Vasseur — Does De Giorgi Offer a Different Path?
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:773:missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:321:3. **Velocity nonlinear term:** Vasseur achieves exponent 5/3 > 3/2, which is better than CKN's critical 3/2 exponent. The De Giorgi level-set mechanism "beats" the natural NS scaling for the velocity term.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:775:missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:331:3. **The dimension bound ≤ 1 arises through the same route:** Global energy bound ∫∫|∇u|² < ∞ → Vitali cover → Σ r_i ≤ C||∇u||²_{L²} → H¹(S) = 0. The De Giorgi iteration is used to establish the epsilon-regularity criterion; once established, the covering argument is identical to CKN.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:776:missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:333:4. **Full regularity is not achieved:** Both proofs face an exponent barrier. In CKN, it is the natural NS scaling (3/2 exponent for the nonlinear term). In Vasseur, the barrier is at exponent 4/3 from the local pressure term — actually a *harder* obstruction (lower exponent), though still > 1.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:777:missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:337:Vasseur's proof does NOT offer a new route around the dimension ≤ 1 bottleneck. The De Giorgi mechanism achieves superlinear feedback (β > 1) via a different algebraic route, but the covering argument reduces to the same inequality Σ r_i ≤ C∫|∇u|² that CKN uses. The dimension bound is not a consequence of the particular proof technique; it is a consequence of the global energy bound and the ε-regularity structure — which are shared by all three proofs.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:778:missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:339:**What Vasseur's proof does offer** is a structural identification of the obstruction to full regularity: the local pressure term P_k^{21} gives exponent 4/3, and Vasseur proves (Appendix) that β > 3/2 would imply full regularity. So Vasseur's framework converts the question "can we prove full regularity?" into "can we control the local pressure term with exponent > 3/2?" — a more precise formulation than CKN provides.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:781:missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/lin-1998-proof-architecture.md:135:(a) **Pressure decomposition:** CKN's explicit cutoff-function approach requires decomposing p = p_1 + p_2 (Riesz-transform part + harmonic part) and estimating each piece explicitly. Lin's compactness argument absorbs this decomposition into the "the limit is well-defined" step — the pressure control is needed to ensure compactness, but it appears as a background condition (p ∈ L^{3/2}) rather than an explicit estimate.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:782:missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/lin-1998-proof-architecture.md:229:| Y1 (pressure-velocity Hölder in LEI) | Hidden in "suitable weak solution" definition | No |
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:790:missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:241:By the CKN pressure decomposition technique (see CKN §3, and Robinson-Rodrigo-Sadowski Ch.13 §13.3), p_2 is controlled by the non-local part of the pressure, which in turn is bounded by global L^{3/2} norms of u far from x₀.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:792:missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:397:**Young Step Y4: The absorption step in the CKN "pressure-regularity" lemma**
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:797:missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:515:**On Ladyzhenskaya-Seregin (1999):** They simplify the pressure decomposition step (avoiding the harmonic splitting p = p₁ + p₂ by working in a different functional framework), but the ε-regularity criterion and covering argument are identical to CKN.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:798:missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:517:**On Robinson-Rodrigo-Sadowski (2016):** Their Chapter 13 presents the CKN proof in full, including the explicit form of the local energy inequality and the parabolic Sobolev embedding. Their §13.3 has the most explicit treatment of the pressure decomposition.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:918:missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/REPORT-SUMMARY.md:4:Extract five structural features from Vasseur's 2007 De Giorgi proof of partial regularity for Navier-Stokes and compare with CKN (1982).
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:919:missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/REPORT-SUMMARY.md:14:Vasseur's Theorem 1 states: if sup_t ∫_{B(1)} |u|² + ∫∫|∇u|² + ||P||_{L^p(L¹)}^2 ≤ C*, then u is bounded on the inner half-cylinder. This is stated at **fixed scale** on a unit cylinder — not in CKN's "for all r → 0" form. The CKN criterion E(u,r) < δ* is recovered as Theorem 2 via standard NS parabolic rescaling; Vasseur claims no novelty there. The pressure condition is weaker than CKN: P ∈ L^p(L¹) for any p > 1 (vs. CKN's P ∈ L^{3/2}).
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:920:missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/REPORT-SUMMARY.md:20:The core novelty. Vasseur defines decreasing cylinders Q_k → Q_∞ = [−1/2,1]×B(1/2) with increasing levels C_k = 1−2^{−k} → 1, tracking the level-set energy U_k = sup_t ∫|v_k|² + ∫∫ d_k² where v_k = [|u|−C_k]₊. The master inequality (Lemma 11 + Eq. 13) gives U_k ≤ C^k·(1+||P||_{L^p(L¹)})·U_{k−1}^{β_p} with β_p > 1. The key departure from CKN: the pressure is decomposed into a harmonic (non-local) part P_k^1 controlled by the single global norm ||P||_{L^p(L¹)}, plus a local part P_k^2 depending only on u inside B_{k−1}. This avoids the need for P ∈ L^{3/2}(Q_r) at every scale r → 0.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:921:missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/REPORT-SUMMARY.md:23:Parabolic Sobolev: L² energy → L^{10/3} (the critical exponent 2·5/3 for parabolic dimension 5 = 3+2). De Giorgi level sets give U_{k−1}^{5/3} for transport/velocity terms (better than CKN's 3/2). But the local pressure term P_k^{21} yields exponent β → 4/3 (as q → ∞). Summary: velocity terms β = 5/3 > 3/2 (De Giorgi beats CKN here); pressure β = 4/3 < 3/2 (new bottleneck). Net: β_p > 1 for all p > 1 → partial regularity; β_p < 3/2 in general → full regularity not achieved. Vasseur shows in an Appendix that β > 3/2 would imply **full regularity** — so the threshold 3/2 is precise.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:922:missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/REPORT-SUMMARY.md:26:No per-step ε-absorption in the De Giorgi iteration (unlike CKN). The only free parameter is λ (chosen once in Proposition 5 to make a linear coefficient < 1/8). Lossiness is fixed by: geometric factors 2^{Ck} from cutoffs (absorbed into C^k in Lemma 4) and the hard exponent 4/3 from the local pressure term — not a proof artifact, but a structural obstruction. De Giorgi is strictly less lossy on the velocity side (5/3 vs 3/2 for transport terms) but encounters a new pressure bottleneck.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:923:missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/REPORT-SUMMARY.md:29:Vasseur's De Giorgi proof arrives at dimension ≤ 1 via the **same Vitali covering applied to the same ε-regularity criterion** as CKN. The De Giorgi mechanism is used only to establish the ε-regularity threshold; once established, the dimension bound follows the CKN route. The structural bottleneck (H¹(S) = 0 but not H^α(S) = 0 for α < 1) is not a consequence of proof technique — it reflects the global energy bound and parabolic scaling, shared by all approaches. Vasseur's value-add is a sharper identification of the full-regularity obstruction: the local pressure term contributes exponent 4/3 < 3/2, and 3/2 is precisely the threshold for full regularity.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:925:missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/REPORT-SUMMARY.md:38:- The De Giorgi approach actually produces a *worse* pressure exponent (4/3 < 3/2) than CKN's direct pressure estimate, even though it requires only the weaker pressure condition P ∈ L^p(L¹). This means the "weaker assumptions → same conclusion" improvement comes at the cost of a harder internal obstruction.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:957:missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-002/REPORT.md:135:(a) **Pressure decomposition:** CKN's explicit cutoff-function approach requires decomposing p = p_1 + p_2 (Riesz-transform part + harmonic part) and estimating each piece explicitly. Lin's compactness argument absorbs this decomposition into the "the limit is well-defined" step — the pressure control is needed to ensure compactness, but it appears as a background condition (p ∈ L^{3/2}) rather than an explicit estimate.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:958:missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-002/REPORT.md:229:| Y1 (pressure-velocity Hölder in LEI) | Hidden in "suitable weak solution" definition | No |
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:994:missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/GOAL.md:5:Analyze Alexis Vasseur's proof (2007) of partial regularity for Navier-Stokes using De Giorgi iteration. Extract the structural features that determine the dimension bound on the singular set, with particular attention to how Vasseur's approach differs from CKN (1982) and Lin (1998).
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:995:missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/GOAL.md:15:- CKN and Lin use scaled energy quantities involving ∫|∇u|² and pressure terms over parabolic cylinders.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:1000:missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/GOAL.md:28:- CKN uses cutoff functions; Lin uses compactness. What does De Giorgi iteration do instead?
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:1002:missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/GOAL.md:31:- What new estimates or inequalities does the De Giorgi approach require that CKN doesn't?
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:1003:missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/GOAL.md:32:- Is the De Giorgi approach more or less lossy than CKN's cutoff approach?
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:1005:missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/GOAL.md:38:- Does the De Giorgi approach produce the dimension ≤ 1 bound through the same scaling route as CKN, or through a genuinely different mechanism?
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:1007:missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/GOAL.md:44:- Are the estimates in the De Giorgi approach "tighter" than CKN in any identifiable way?
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:1008:missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/GOAL.md:51:- Clear identification of what the De Giorgi approach changes vs. what it preserves from the CKN framework
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:1010:missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/GOAL.md:57:- Treating Vasseur's proof as "just another proof of CKN" without extracting what the De Giorgi iteration specifically changes
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:1163:missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/REPORT.md:5:Analyze Alexis Vasseur's 2007 proof of partial regularity for Navier-Stokes equations using De Giorgi iteration. Extract five structural features and compare with CKN (1982).
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:1164:missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/REPORT.md:9:**Sources consulted:** Vasseur 2007 preprint; Vasseur lecture notes (DGPekin.pdf); CKN Seminar Notes Ulm 2019 (Skipper); Seregin-Shilkin survey arXiv:1402.7181; Lee REU paper 2024 (De Giorgi for fluids).
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:1165:missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/REPORT.md:27:1. **No pressure L^{3/2} norm.** The pressure P enters only via P ∈ L^p_t(L¹_x) for any p > 1. This is weaker than CKN's P ∈ L^{3/2} (in space-time) and weaker than L^p(L^{5/3}) used elsewhere. The L¹ spatial integrability is much weaker — only the time Sobolev regularity (p > 1) is needed.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:1166:missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/REPORT.md:29:2. **Fixed scale, not shrinking.** The domain [−1,1]×B(1) does not shrink as the proof proceeds. The De Giorgi cylinders Q_k converge to [−1/2,1]×B(1/2) from the outside. This is the fundamental structural departure from CKN, where the epsilon-regularity criterion is stated as a condition at every radius r → 0.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:1169:missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/REPORT.md:83:The covering argument is entirely at the level of Theorem 2 — the De Giorgi iteration (Theorem 1) is used only to establish Theorem 2, after which the CKN covering machinery runs unchanged.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:1177:missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/REPORT.md:155:**CKN's pressure difficulty.** In CKN, the pressure P satisfies −ΔP = ∂_i∂_j(u_iu_j) globally. Localizing this to a parabolic cylinder Q_r requires Riesz transform estimates, generating error terms of the form ∫|u|² (on larger balls). This introduces a nonlocal term that is hard to control at each scale and requires P ∈ L^{3/2}(Q_r) explicitly.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:1182:missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/REPORT.md:170:**Why this works at fixed scale but not at shrinking scale:** The key insight is that ||P||_{L^p(L¹)} is a *single global number* that doesn't scale with k. In CKN, you would need ||P||_{L^{3/2}(Q_{r_k})} at each level r_k → 0, which requires the full pressure integrability. Here, the single global norm suffices because Q_k → Q_∞ ≠ 0.
../../../../runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-001-curator-001.log:1195:missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/REPORT.md:257:Vasseur's transport terms give **5/3 > 3/2** (better than CKN), but the local pressure term gives **4/3 < 3/2** (worse, in the sense of being farther from full regularity). So:
